<paragraph id="8BD1946CFE60581B01F431D9FC96F9D8" blockId="3.[136,1452,1179,1926]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">
Interestingly, the specimen from 
<collectingCountry id="F379D4FCFE60581B037E31D9FD07FB38" box="[567,691,1251,1277]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
shares with the Honduran type the position and orientation of the triquetrous blades of the lip, whose apices, as Ames noted in the protologue, bent down to become closely appressed to and almost touching the lateral sepals (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFFE99DFE60581B032E3011FCB8FA80" author="Ames, O." box="[615,780,1323,1349]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" pagination="3 - 8" refId="ref4435" refString="Ames, O. (1933) The Honduran species of Lepanthes. Botanical Museum Leaflets, Harvard University 4: 3 - 8." type="journal article" year="1933">Ames 1933: 8</bibRefCitation>
). It seems that this feature is typical of the true 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B04713011FF41FAAC" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B04713011FF41FAAC" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Lepanthes edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as this orientation of the blades is absent in the species we previously discussed and illustrated from 
<collectingCountry id="F379D4FCFE60581B04253075FF0FFA48" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
under that name.Apparently, the flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B03E93049FC31FA48" box="[672,901,1395,1421]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B03E93049FC31FA48" box="[672,901,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Lepanthes edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may assume both a resupinate and non-resupinate orientation. Even though Blanche Ames illustrated the flowers of the type plant as regularly non-resupinate (
<figureCitation id="135588E9FE60581B041130ADFA2EFA74" box="[1368,1434,1431,1457]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1985,2007]" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lepanthes edwardsii. Illustration of type by Blanche Ames, from Ames 1933." pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the plants mounted on the 
<typeStatus id="54D52ACEFE60581B00FA3081FDA1FA10" box="[435,533,1467,1493]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">holotype</typeStatus>
sheet (
<collectionCode id="ED7F0CA9FE60581B03243081FD09FA10" box="[621,701,1467,1493]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15408" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15408" name="Harvard University - Oakes Ames Orchid Herbarium" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" type="Herbarium">AMES</collectionCode>
00100585) present flowers with both kinds of orientation (
<figureCitation id="135588E9FE60581B04113081FA28FA10" box="[1368,1436,1467,1493]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1353,1375]" captionTargetBox="[190,1395,175,1328]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[190,1396,175,1328]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Lepanthes edwardsii. Specimens mounted on the holotype sheet (AMES 39045 / Barcode 00100585). Note the resupinate flower on the specimen above on the right, the non-resupinate flower in the lower, right specimen, and the horizontal flower on the specimen on the lower left. Reproduced with kind permission of the Keeper, AMES Herbarium, Harvard University Herbaria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414741/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), and in most photographs of this species that we had the opportunity to observe, as well as in the living specimen we studied from 
<collectingCountry id="F379D4FCFE60581B00543339FE2EF9D8" box="[285,410,1539,1565]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, the flowers are always resupinate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD1946CFE60581B01F4331DFB71F8DC" blockId="3.[136,1452,1179,1926]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">
The plant that Luer (in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFFE99DFE60581B00813312FD0AF984" author="Luer, C. A. &amp; Thoerle, L." box="[456,702,1575,1602]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 296" refId="ref4957" refString="Luer, C. A. &amp; Thoerle, L. (2012) Icones Pleurothallidinarum XXXII, Lepanthes of Colombia (Orchidaceae). Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 123: 1 - 296." type="journal article" year="2012">Luer &amp; Thoerle 2012</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 100) illustrated from 
<collectingCountry id="F379D4FCFE60581B02A2331DFBEDF984" box="[1003,1113,1575,1601]" name="Colombia" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Colombia</collectingCountry>
under the name of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B0471331DFF41F9A0" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B0471331DFF41F9A0" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Lepanthes edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B004E3376FE77F9A3" box="[263,451,1611,1638]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">
Luer 11629, 
<collectionCode id="ED7F0CA9FE60581B00DE3376FE77F9A3" box="[407,451,1612,1638]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15859" name="Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" type="Herbarium">MO</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
), with resupinate flowers, appears to be only distantly related to the Honduran 
<typeStatus id="54D52ACEFE60581B04033376FACEF9A3" box="[1354,1402,1612,1638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">type</typeStatus>
and could belong instead to a still undescribed taxon. The blades of lip of the Colombian specimen are thick, hemielliptic, and the appendix is broad and short, while the shape of the petals is closer to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B056C33AEFB77F968" authorityName="Bogarin &amp; Pupulin" authorityYear="2014" box="[1061,1219,1683,1709]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="durikaensis">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B056C33AEFB77F968" box="[1061,1219,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">L. durikaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B045333AEFA10F968" box="[1306,1444,1683,1709]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B045333AEFA10F968" box="[1306,1444,1683,1709]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">L. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Another Colombian record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B0097338DFD72F914" box="[478,710,1719,1745]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B0097338DFD72F914" box="[478,710,1719,1745]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Lepanthes edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been documented by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFFE99DFE60581B02A4338DFAF7F914" author="Misas Urreta, G." box="[1005,1347,1719,1746]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" refId="ref4997" refString="Misas Urreta, G. (2005) Orquideas de la Serrania del Baudo, Choco, Colombia / Orchids from the Serrania del Baudo Choco, Colombia. Corporacion Capitalina de Orquideologia - Zona Ediciones, Bogota." type="book" year="2005">Misas Urreta (2005: 280–281)</bibRefCitation>
from the Serranía del Baudó, a low mountain range on the Pacific coast, also with resupinate flowers, but according to the author the lobes of the lip are conical, and the illustration shows the ramicauls marginally hispid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD1946CFE60581B01F43219FB83F843" blockId="3.[136,1452,1179,1926]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">
The discovery of a Costa Rican population of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B039D3219FCF3F8F8" authorityName="Swartz" authorityYear="1799" box="[724,839,1827,1853]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B039D3219FCF3F8F8" box="[724,839,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">Lepanthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that can be confidently associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C6EEFEFFE60581B045E321EFA10F8F8" box="[1303,1444,1827,1853]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis id="B91A487EFE60581B045E321EFA10F8F8" box="[1303,1444,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="72">L. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, leaves without a proper name the taxon that 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFFE99DFE60581B0331327DFC2AF8A4" author="Pupulin, F. &amp; Bogarin, D." box="[632,926,1863,1889]" pageId="3" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref5294" refString="Pupulin, F. &amp; Bogarin, D. (2014) Illustrations and studies in Neotropical Orchidaceae. 6. The Lepanthes guatemalensis group (Pleurothallidinae) in Costa Rica. Anales del Jardin Botanico de Madrid 71: 1 - 17. https: // doi. org / 10.3989 / ajbm. 2388" type="journal article" year="2014">Pupulin &amp; Bogarín (2014)</bibRefCitation>
discussed previously as local representative of that species. It is therefore proposed here as a species new to science with the name:
</paragraph>
